How to make a scatter plot

I first start experimenting with ggplot2 using the mpg library:

head(mpg)

I start producing the simplest plot without any other layer:

ggplot(midwest, aes( x= area, y=poptotal))

Then I can start adding layers on top of this one, like using the command geom_point() and adding it (+) to the object:

ggplot(midwest, aes( x= area, y=poptotal)) + geom_point()

I can start making it more beautiful adding a fit line as well as a confidence interval area:

g <- ggplot(midwest, aes( x= area, y=poptotal)) + geom_point(col = "red", size = 0.9) + geom_smooth(method = "lm")

Adjusting the X and Y axis limits

I can make it look better in two ways:

  1. Zooming in (without removing outliers or influential observations)

  2. Deleting points outside the range

Zooming in

I make use of the command coord_cartesian() and specifying the xlim and ylim that I wish to zoom in into:

g1 <- g + coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0,0.1), ylim = c(0,1000000)) 
plot(g1)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Deleting outliers

I can delete the points outside the limits by using the same xlim and ylim and specifying limits (in this case from 0,0.1 in the x-axis and 0,1e+6 in y-axis). Because these are influential observations, I can also plot over this truncated linear fit line with the zoomed version to see how the slope changes:

g <- ggplot(midwest, aes(x= area, y=poptotal)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm") # Generate plot
g + xlim(c(0, 0.1)) + ylim(c(0, 1000000))  # Delete points
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Application to Demographic Analysis

This is an application to my ECON-3779 homework. First I construct 4 vectors and turn them into a dataframe:

one <- c(0.085, 0.081, 0.0567, 0.0364, 0.0526, 0.0526, 0.0283, 0.0769, 0.0405, 0.2024, 0.085, 0.0405, 0.0202, 0.0121, 0.0486, 0.0243, 0.0445, 0.004, 0.0081) 
two <- c(0.085, 0.081, 0.0567, 0.0364, 0.0526, 0.0526, 0.0283, 0.0769, 0.0405, 0.0202, 0.0085, 0.004, 0.002, 0.0012, 0.0049, 0.0024, 0.0045, 0.0004, 0.0008)
three <- one/two
odd <- c(rep(0, 9), rep(1, 10))
df <- data_frame(one, two, three, odd)
## Warning: `data_frame()` was deprecated in tibble 1.1.0.
## Please use `tibble()` instead.
## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.
## Call `lifecycle::last_lifecycle_warnings()` to see where this warning was generated.
df

Then I try graphing it using a different variable as a categorical variable to identify the change:

df$odd <- factor(df$odd) # firsst convert numerical variable to factor
plot <- ggplot(data = df, mapping = aes(x= one, y = two)) +
  geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope =1, col = "firebrick", size = 0.5, linetype=2) + 
  geom_point(aes(col=odd))+
  geom_smooth(aes(col=odd))
  
view(plot)
plot + theme_bw() + labs(title="Odd behavior of 1")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data = df) + geom_point(mapping = aes( x = one, y = two), color = blue)
